data.jamchart_notes: No jam makes a bigger case that 2023 is the Year of Big T like this one. Aggressive bass thumping leads to an epic Trevor solo and funk-strutting, blazing finish.

data.jamchart_notes: Patient, building funkfest. Great example of the band locking in and no one taking less, resulting in fantastic collective jamming.
data.shownotes: This show featured the debut of "Empress," Rick's first custom DeLuis guitar.

data.jamchart_notes: Opens the second set with 20 mins of pure fire. Peter leans into some vicious clav riffing as the energy peaks and saves Rick on a technical difficulty. Brief minute of major key jamming and they wrap it up on a strong note.

data.jamchart_notes: Trevor driving as he often does with "Thatch," but this time with simple-yet-cool riffs and melodies that the band latches onto and then builds around. Stank face inducing rock in the last 6 minutes.
data.shownotes: What's Up was played for the first time since October 7, 2022 (67 shows).

data.jamchart_notes: Jam quickly mellows out into a quiet-yet-tight groove. "Tequila" teasing adds some flavour as the band gradually increases the energy and explodes. Amazing mid-set version from the legendary SPAC debut.
data.shownotes: This was Goose's biggest headlining show to date.
data.soundcheck: This Old Sea, Factory Fiction, Please Forgive Me (this soundcheck is incomplete)

data.jamchart_notes: Dark and synthy. Learning lessons from each version on the road to Boston, this one has some amazing eerie texturing from Peter, while Rick and Trevor growl in the darkness. Gradually picks up steam with the same ominous Prophet synth undertone throughout. Excellent display of tension-building here.

Whether you think it's the JOTY or not, this "Thatch" is a seriously dense listen. Dark and percussive at first, it feels very typical for the tour but quickly heads into evil territory thanks to Rick and Peter's interplay. Spuds pivots into a charging beat at the 18th minute and they just go for it. Superlatives can't even do this peak justice - needs to be listened. Rick plays with his Whammy at the apex before they execute a perfect and towering return to the song proper. All-timer.
data.shownotes: The Killing Moon was played for the first time since November 7, 2020 (190 shows). Moby was played for the first time since January 15, 2023 (55 shows).

data.jamchart_notes: While many previous versions of "Thatch" highlight an aggressive or darker jam, this LA version turns bright and contemplative after a turn of percussive play with strong Trevor and Peter underneath Rick's melodies. Hints of the Vegas "Elizabeth" to come a few days later.
data.shownotes: Peter teased Charge! before the second set.

data.jamchart_notes: Continuation of the mellower and more upbeat "Thatch" style seen at the Wiltern on 9/28. Rocking first half transitions into a quieter space that builds into an excellent peak.

data.footnote: With Texas and The Landlady teases.

data.jamchart_notes: Peter collects a bunch of coins early on as the rhythm section destroys the minimalist funk groove. Rick pivots into triumph and the band unleashes a volcanic peak to close it out.
After funky start where Luigi finds his coins, Peter layers mystical synths and Rick finds a haunting repeating riff that propels a wonderfully unique and enchanting version. Thrilling finish.

data.footnote: With Carol Of The Bells teases from Rick and Give Up The Funk tease from Trevor.

data.jamchart_notes: Dark and propulsive jam led by Peter on the OB-6. Not the deepest improvisationally but an excellent listen.

data.jamchart_notes: Circular patterns of tension and darkness develop as Cotter's fluidity shines. Builds layers and layers of unease as Peter hits sirens and Rick gets dissonant. Amazing stuff that can be likened to a mid-90s "Stash."

Blazing second set version sees the band lock in around Trevor's thumping and Peter's arpeggiator. Hypnotic groove develops and hits a peak but is brought to its conclusion by Rick before it can go any further.
data.shownotes: This show was part of the Northlands Music and Arts Festival.

data.jamchart_notes: You enjoy this jam, beginning with some squishy OB-6 work from Peter and eventually shifting into a flowing rock zone that might inspire you to jump on trampolines.

Big second-set version comes on the heels of a special Autumn Crossing performance. The band strips down to minimalist funk initially with Peter really going ham with delay on the clav. All five members unite as one and rip through a sustained peak section with no one person in the lead.
data.shownotes: This was the band’s biggest headlining show to date.

data.jamchart_notes: Listen for that earworm riff Peter picks up on Vibe. Excellent sustained peak.
Shades of 6/19/21 "Madhuvan" and 11/18/23 "All I Need" as the band cools things off and flips on a tension/release alternating jam.

data.jamchart_notes: Aggressive Rick and nice tension-building.

data.jamchart_notes: Precursor to what will come in Cincy a week later, the band lets the groove dictate where things will go before getting into an excellent peak, though it stays pretty close to "Thatch" form throughout.
data.shownotes: Wild Night was played for the first time since July 3, 2023 (98 shows).

data.jamchart_notes: Peter pulls several incredible earworms out of nowhere early on as Rick hangs back on minimalist rhythm. Trevor suggests a progression that will inform the rest of the jam as all five band members listen incredibly closely to each other. The key here is restraint from Rick - and when he finally lets go for the peak, it's nothing short of spectacular. MUST-HEAR.
data.shownotes: The encore featured the live debut of "Dracul," Rick's new DeLuis guitar.

data.jamchart_notes: Standard ragefest notable for its dip into Westville "Rockdale" territory for some unsettling runs ahead of the final peak.

Silky smooth late-2024 transition hardly needs any time within "Thatch" proper before the improv unfurls like a flower into a gorgeous bliss jam. Coasts along effortlessly before dissolving unfinished for the first time ever into an encore break-spanning synth drone.
data.shownotes: The Labyrinth was played for the first time since June 20, 2024 (51 shows). I2I was played for the first time since June 15, 2019 (382 shows).

data.jamchart_notes: The younger sibling of 11/8/24. Peter summons a sampled ocean wave (no, seriously) and the band builds a linear-yet-exciting jam from nothing to an extended peak that Rick just won't let go.

data.shownotes: This show was part of the New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival.

data.jamchart_notes: Festival-closing insanity. The band dives headlong into breakneck speed Westville "Rockdale" jamming, Rick and Peter in particular chasing each other through a wild tension-filled chase. Trevor uses some deep synth pedals while Cotter propels the whole thing with insistent percussion hits. The evil eventually explodes back into the song proper, but a sly double-time shift on the drums leads to another dip into wild dissonance before coming home. Outstanding version.
data.shownotes: This show was part of the inaugural Viva El Gonzo festival. How it Ends was played for the first time since April 10, 2024 (82 shows).

data.jamchart_notes: Hearkens back to 7/7/23 at the outset with thick, melodic clav lines from Peter. Transitions into airy, major key jamming - though never hits a true peak - before Rick pulls them into a new, calm space. Building in intensity around a quick-hit motif, the band works in beautiful harmony through a big, explosive passage. Cotter hits the double-time from there for a turn toward the darkness, Trevor leading things into an evil descending progression that sticks around through the explosive "Thatch" ending.

data.jamchart_notes: Second-set opening version at The Garden gets going with some airy sauce from Rick. The band then departs from the funk atop a fluid groove from Cotter and push into a major key. Familiar emotional guitar-led jamming dominates from there, each band member relishing in the accomplishment of this monumental show. Trevor really shines with some active high-register bass lines before things explode back home.

data.jamchart_notes: Solid (if not standard) "Thatch" jamming detours into some evil tension spaces ahead of the final peak.

data.shownotes: The show began where the previous show left off - Rick walked up on stage and turned on the light as a choir began to sing a drone off stage. The choir then joined after the first chorus. During Marb House, a UV Dance Party commenced with characters dancing on stage and painting all the set props with UV paint. During the encore all of the characters and puppets appeared as well as two aerialists. There was also a balloon drop and confetti during Dramophone. The show ended with the veil opening back up, after the veil sequence, the characters, puppets, choir, and band had vanished. This show was part of Goosemas XII.
